http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 9 Jun 2014
Source: OIE, WAHID (World Animal Health Information Database), weekly disease information 2014; 27(24) [edited]
http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=15389


Porcine epidemic diarrhea virus, Colombia
-----------------------------------------
Information received on [and dated] 9 Jun 2014 from Dr Luis Humberto Martinez Lacouture, [general manager, Colombian Agricultural Institute, (ICA), Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development], Bogota, Colombia

Summary
Report type: immediate notification (final report)
Date of start of the event: 7 Mar 2014
Date of pre-confirmation of the event: 8 May 2014
Date event resolved: 9 Jun 2014
Reason for notification: emerging disease
Morbidity: 18 per cent
Mortality: 6 per cent
Zoonotic impact: no zoonotic potential
Causal agent: porcine epidemic diarrhea virus
Serotype: other

New outbreaks: 45
Outbreak cluster 1: San Fernando, Las Brisas, Casco urbano, La Palmita, Los Tamarindos, Las Bateas, Buenavista, La Angostura, Granja Orion, Neiva, Villa Vieja, Guadalupe, Tello, Huila (12 outbreaks)
Date of start of the outbreak: 7 Mar 2014
Outbreak status: resolved (9 Jun 2014)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Swine / 3946 / 750 / 426 / 0 / 0
Affected population: 12 outbreaks affecting mainly backyard farms with semi-confined animals. Quick recovery of the animals is observed.

Outbreak cluster 2: Villa Rosita, El Porvenir, San Sebastian, and others, Fusagasuga, Silvania, La Mesa, Granada, La Calera, Choachi, Tibacuy, San Antonio del Tequendama, Cundinamarca (30 outbreaks)
Date of start of the outbreak: 8 Mar 2014
Outbreak status: resolved (9 Jun 2014)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Swine / 14 272 / 2476 / 564 / 0 / 0
Affected population: 30 outbreaks located mainly in commercial farms. Backyard farms have also been affected.

Outbreak 3: Don Rafa, Urbano, Ibague, Tolima
Date of start of the outbreak: 4 Apr 2014
Outbreak status: resolved (9 Jun 2014)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Swine / 9 / 3 / 3 / 0 / 0
Affected population: animals located in the urban area of the municipality, backyard farm with confined animals.

Outbreak 4: Portales, Chiguata, Tibana, Boyaca
Date of start of the outbreak: 24 Apr 2014
Outbreak status: resolved (9 Jun 2014)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Swine / 27 / 27 / 21 / 0 / 0
Affected population: backyard farm with confined animals. Animals fed on swill. Poor health conditions.

Outbreak 5: Vista Hermosa, Rayitos, Lebrija, Santander
Date of start of the outbreak: 12 May 2014
Outbreak status: resolved (9 Jun 2014)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Swine / 298 / 72 / 40 / 0 / 0
Affected population: commercial farm

Summary of outbreaks
Total outbreaks: 45
Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Swine / 18 552 / 3328 / 1054 / 0 / 0
Outbreak statistics [rates apparent, expressed as percentages]
Species / Morbidity rate / Mortality rate / Case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Swine / 17.9 / 5.7 / 31.7 / 5.7
*Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction, and/or slaughter

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive; introduction of new live animals; legal movement of animals; illegal movement of animals; swill feeding; fomites (human, vehicles, feed, etc.)
Epidemiological comments: in March [2014], following an unusual acute diarrhea in pigs (diarrhea and death in piglets), the Colombian Agricultural Institute [ICA] implemented the following measures in order to identify the disease and control it: health emergency status, quarantine on suspected premises, cleaning and disinfection, movement control, enhanced biosecurity measures, ban on animal gathering, active surveillance, inclusion in the information system as a notifiable disease and epidemiological surveillance, among others. There have been 45 outbreaks affecting commercial and backyard farms mainly in the Departments of Cundinamarca and Huila (42 outbreaks) as well as one sporadic outbreak each in the Departments of Tolima, Boyaca, and Santander. Low morbidity and mortality rates are observed, very different from those observed in other countries as United States of America, Canada, and Mexico, and farms recover their production levels in less than 2 weeks. As it is a disease never observed in the country, samples were sent to the Plum Island Animal Disease Center in the United States of America in order to confirm the causal agent by RRT-PCR, virus isolation and sequencing. On 6 Jun 2014, the USDA confirmed in a preliminary report by RRT-PCR and sequencing that samples submitted were similar to the porcine epidemic diarrhea virus reported in the United States of America but different to the virus observed in Asia.

Control measures
Measures applied: quarantine; movement control inside the country; disinfection of infected premises/establishment(s); vaccination prohibited; treatment of affected animals (symptomatic)
Measures to be applied: no other measures

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Test / Test date / Result
Plum Island Animal Disease Center (USA) (foreign laboratory) / swine / real-time reverse transcriptase/polymerase chain reaction (RRT-PCR) / 8 May 2014 / Positive
Plum Island Animal Disease Center (USA) (foreign laboratory) / swine / virus sequencing / 6 Jun 2014 / Positive

Future reporting
The event is resolved. No more reports will be submitted.

[The location of the outbreaks can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

